For the selectivity, the five pesticides as mentioned above were analysed. As shown in (Fig. 7a and 8

                        ) the FL intensities were recovered by enhancing the concentration of MP-OP. It was observed that the other five pesticides also followed the linear relationship with the concentration (Fig. 7b–f) as MP-OP. However, their fluorescence behaviour was seen as different from that of MP-OP, showing a distinct "turn off-on" fluorescence concept. A linear relationship between the concentration of MP-OP and fluorescence intensity was observed with a mean correlation coefficient of 0.98 (Fig. 6c). The linearity and uncertainty of the curve were calculated and presented in Table 2
                        . The LOD and LOQ were found to be 0.012 ppm and 0.035 ppm respectively. The low LOD and LOQ showed that the C-dots probe solution is effective in quenching the desired pesticides. Recovery of pesticides when analysed using C-dots probe solution were observed from 90 to 102.5 %, which confirmed that the C-dots probe solutions were effective to analyze the methyl parathion effectively. The findings of C-dots probe solution for pesticides concentration ranging from 0.04 ppm to 0.1 ppm were compared with the findings of Gas chromatography (GC) (chromatogram is not presented here) (Table 3
                        ). Variation between the findings of GC and C-dots probe solution were in the range of −5.33 to 13.33 %.
